title: For Sale:  20 Gage Flintlock Fowler; An original, custom flint; (OBO)
location: Cary, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Here it is people! I have for sale, 62 cal smooth bore single trigger fowler. Furniture is iron and lock left white. There is moderate recessed engraving on the stock and no nose cap. _____The flint was designed to be a high quality hunting "jack of all trades" and accomplishes this very well. _____I had the flintlock made approximately 10 years ago by Miller of NC and then was injured overseas and am not able to hunt any more. It seems to be a waste leaving the gun in the vault as it only had one day at the range. _____The trigger is great and finish excellent. Will make an excellent primitive hunting rifle or re-enactment flintlock. _____ Tried to catch all details in the pictures. Please ask questions first. ____ Answer to a question from a prospective buyer: The length of barrel is 41". The pull is 13 1/2".___ This weapon handles great, points excellent, and is very light for all day hunting.___ You can shoot ball through it...I didn't want to choke the gun so I could shoot ball through it and make it a sort of "Jack-of-all-trades". This was going to be my one gun that could do it all that's why I went with one trigger and a single sight. The barrel came from a high quality blank. It has the "sitting fox" trade stamp on it.___ Another prospective buyer's question: What type of wood is the stock and what the overall length? The stock is walnut. The barrel length is 41" and the total rifle length is 57".___ Another answer to a email question: What diameter ball have you shot out of the rifle? I've shot .610" ball out of this particular rifle. _____Another email "How are springs and fit of pan to frizzen? Sometimes these have weak mainsprings. Bore clean? Thanks Bsusmc":____The mainspring is extremely strong with the right amount of effort required to "cock" the hammer. In fact, it is a little stiff as the weapon has been hot very little and stored (OFC) with the hammer down ensuring the spring was not in a compressed position. The fit of the frizzen and pan has very little "lateral" movement and was very well fit to the flintlock. There are not the "slop" that developed after time with a poorly aligned frizzen. Allen Miller does a very good job making sure that all the pieces of the firearm are constructed with hand tools. We know that’s very important as modern tools tend to take off so much material in such a fast manner that everyone just slops it together and has to use adhesive to fill in the excessive spaces that are created.__The flintlock was taken out very few times and the bore was immediately cleaned with boiling water until it ran clear and then a ramrod with soft bore brush soaked in "bore butter" was applied. I think the flintlock only saw 3 range sessions at best and I cleared the bore before and after each session.____Remember, No FFL required, legally ships to your door!____ PLEASE TAKE NOTICE: The market is flooded with second-rate imported copies of these rifles.___Before you buy, Do your research and I think you'll find a quality, original, American piece such as this, is hard to come by for this price. In hindsight, you'll be glad you chose a true original American flintlock. 

Price is $750 OBO, will ship continental USA at actual shipping cost.

title: For Sale:  AK. AR. SKS.
postcontent:
ARMSLIST and all other gun marketplaces are community run for the most part. As a gun community we need to come together to rid ourselves of one of the deadliest sins - greed. We are all tired of seeing $500 AK-47s listed at $2000, and $800 fully upgraded AR-15s posted for $4500. Guess what? As gun buyers and members on this and other forums, we are just as responsible for the state of our society as the price gougers and hoarders. We need to come together and do two thing: (1) STOP BUYING AT THESE RIDICULOUS PRICES and (2) click on the ad, go to "Flag" at the top, and press "overpriced." This whole process takes 1.3968 seconds.

These price criminals only have business if someone is ignorant enough to buy and if they spread their advertisement. NOTE TO GUN COMMUNITY: Guns aren't going anywhere. Ammo isn't going anywhere. Magazines are the biggest threat of changing but let's face it, do we really need 100 round drums or is that more of a want? Every time you skip over a $10,000 ad for a $3000 purchased SCAR 17, you have just became part of the problem. Send them a hate email showing the prices before hoarding and then promptly flag their ad so we can get prices back under the 1000s where they all belong. For the uninformed or misinformed audience, I have put together a short list of reasonable prices for standard guns. What I am asking is that everyone read this post and then immediately copy and paste it to another state's listing in the US. Add your own two cents in if you'd like or if I got anything wrong. The regularity will only return if we make it.

AR-15: $600-$1300 depending on brand and usage (shots fired, wear, etc..)
AK-47: $400-$900
SKS:$300-$500
SCAR 16/17: $2000/$2800
AR-10: $1000-1500
Glock: $400-600
10/22: $229
ACR: $2000
1911: $600-1100
9mm ammo: $0.25/round is on the higher end
223/5.56: $0.35/round
.308/7.62 NATO: maybe up to $1/round (on high side)
.22: $0.05/round is high

Again, feel free to add your $0.02, make changes, repost, and then get to the flagging of overpriced scams.
